## Description of major design decisions and changes from Phase 1
The initial Phase 1 design had utilized a pneumatic cylinder that was connected through a ball and socket joint to provide tension for assisting in the bicep in lifting loads, 
with fabric braces positioned along the arm for support. The system was originally intended to support approximately 20 pounds of additional overhead weight.
However, recent feedback from Phase 1 and further design evaluation has resulted in several major changes that were implemented in Phase 2 for improved usability, safety, and mechanical efficiency.

The pneumatic cylinder and pin-based adjustment system were removed and replaced with an updated ratcheting system consisting of a linear pawl, pulley, and gear rack to regulate and 
adjust the tension in the system. Additionally, an archer-style mechanism trigger was introduced, including a cable, claw, and trigger interface, which would allow the user to engage 
and disengage tension with minimal effort. This directly addresses feedback indicating that the system should require less input from the user’s opposite arm.

Several structural changes were adjusted to improve stability and comfort. Two rigid bars were added along the outer portion of the arm, secured with fabric straps, 
replacing the previous brace configuration located between the bicep and forearm. Additionally, the spring has been repositioned to run around the middle length of the user’s arm,
and the archer mechanism has been located near the elbow to better control the release in tension. As a result of relocating the spring and with the new addition of the archer mechanism, 
smoother downward arm motion is attainable. A secondary wheel system has also been introduced to guide and temporarily lock in the disengaged cord until it is manually reset.

The recent modifications introduced in Phase 2 allow for a design that reduces user effort, improves the control of tension, and enhances the reliability of the system while maintaining its intended functional purpose.
